__data__.text: Claude List was born on December 2, 1902, in Maryborough, Queensland, Australia.
Claude's parents were Heinrich (Henry) Wilschefski and Mary Frances Carter.
Henry was born in Germany while Mary was born in Gorton, Lancashire, England.
The families of Claude's parents had both emigrated to Australia in the late 1800s.
Henry and Mary married in 1897.
Claude has two older siblings: Percy Lawrence Wilschefski and Annie Evelyn Wilschefski.
Henry died in Queensland on November 14, 1903, when Claude was just 11 months old.
In 1907, Mary remarried to Francis Martin List who had also been born in Germany.
Francis and Mary had 5 children together, who became Claude's half siblings.
The first born of Francis and Mary's children, Norman Andrew List, died as an infant.
Claude's half siblings, in order of birth, are Alice Holly List, Francis Martin List, Edna Marjorie List, and Irene Maude List.
Sometime between October 1915 and 1919, the family moved to New Zealand.
In 1919, the family lived in Glen Eden, according to census records.
Francis was a senior rugby league player.
Claude started playing rugby league in Queensland as a schoolboy at about the age of 10 in 1912.
After moving to New Zealand, the family settled in Auckland.

In the year 1936, a person named Claude List played 8 senior games for the rugby league team called Mount Albert.
Claude List scored 2 tries during the 1936 season.
Claude List started the 1936 season by playing 2 games for Mount Albert's top side.
In a game against Devonport on May 9, Claude List "did well with limited opportunities".
At the same time, Claude's brother, Francis List, was named in Mount Albert's reserve grade side.
Over the remainder of the 1936 season, Claude List was named in the first grade side in some weeks but not in others.
On May 30, Claude List played against Manukau, a team that had rejoined the competition after years of absence.
Mount Albert won the match 23-18 over the eventual champions, Manukau.
During the match, Claude List "showed up for powerful bursts on occasions".

Claude List either did not play in the other 6 matches or else played for Mount Albert's reserve grade side.
In the year 1937, Claude List played the entire season in reserve grade.
